      <h3 style="font-size: 15px!important;">Procedure</h3>
      the hip joint is a ball and socket joint (whether it is your own or a false hip). The ball and socket are normally very close to each other, but yours have become separated. This means your hip is dislocated. This operation means putting the hip back into the joint.
<br>
      If the surgeon can not do this by just moving the hip, they may try by opening the hip joint by making a cut in the skin and moving the hip directly.
      <h3 style="font-size: 15px!important;">Risks</h3>
      As with all procedures, this carries some risks and complications.<br>
      MOST OF THE COMPLICATIONS BELOW REFER TO AN OPEN REDUCTION<br>
      Pain: this procedure should actually decrease the amount of pain
      by putting the hip in its correct position. If you progress to
      the open reduction (where the surgeon has to make the cut)
      you will be sore around the wound for a short while. You
      must ask for pain killers if you need them.<br>
      Bleeding: This will only occur if you proceed to the operation.<br>
      Scar: the operation will leave a thin on the side of the thigh.
      Infection: This is may present as redness, discharge or temperature around the wound site. A course of antibiotics may be necessary once the source has been isolated.<br>
      Repeat dislocation: once the hip has dislocated once, there is a greater chance
      of it happening again. This may need a further operation to
      correct it if a hip becomes recurrently dislocating.<br>
      Effect of Anaesthesia: anaesthetics can have variable effects, from sickness and
      nausea, to abnormal breathing and heart beats. These
      complications occur rarely.

